---
import WritingLayout from '../../layouts/WritingLayout.astro';
import { writingPosts } from '../../data/writing';

const post = writingPosts.find(p => p.slug === 'backstage-adoption')!;
---

<WritingLayout post={post}>
  <h2>The Plugin Pile Problem</h2>
  <p>
    Most Backstage deployments start the same way: add the software catalog, install a few plugins,
    point it at your GitHub org, and call it an internal developer platform. Then wonder why nobody
    uses it six months later.
  </p>
  <p>
    The problem isn't Backstage. It's treating a developer experience problem like an infrastructure
    problem. You can't deploy your way to adoption. You have to earn it.
  </p>

  <h2>What We Had</h2>
  <p>
    When I inherited the platform, we had Backstage running with:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>A software catalog with 40+ services — mostly auto-discovered, mostly missing owner info</li>
    <li>The TechDocs plugin — documentation that was 6 months stale on most services</li>
    <li>A scaffolder with 3 templates — none of which had been used in 2 months</li>
    <li>A Kubernetes plugin that showed pod status nobody had asked for</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Usage metrics told the story: ~8 unique users per week in an org of 60 engineers.
  </p>

  <h2>The Shift: Treating It Like a Product</h2>
  <p>
    We ran a two-week discovery sprint. Not to add features — to talk to engineers. We asked what
    slowed them down, what they looked up repeatedly, what they wished existed. A few patterns emerged:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Finding who owns a service during an incident took too long (Slack thread archaeology)</li>
    <li>Spinning up a new service meant copying config from an existing one and hoping you didn't miss anything</li>
    <li>Understanding what a service depended on required reading multiple READMEs and pinging people</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    None of these were "we need more plugins." They were catalog quality, template reliability, and
    dependency visibility problems. We already had the tools — they just weren't solving real problems.
  </p>

  <h2>What We Changed</h2>
  <h3>Catalog quality became a blocker, not a nice-to-have</h3>
  <p>
    We added a CI check that fails PRs if the service's <code>catalog-info.yaml</code> is missing
    a valid owner, lifecycle, or system. No more ghost entries. Within a month, 90% of services had
    complete metadata.
  </p>

  <h3>Templates were rewritten with real services as the baseline</h3>
  <p>
    Instead of generic scaffolder templates, we took our two most common service types (REST API,
    async worker) and extracted their exact production configuration into templates. Same Helm chart,
    same Alloy config, same CI pipeline. Engineers got something that actually runs in production on
    day one instead of a skeleton they'd spend a week wiring up.
  </p>

  <h3>We added one plugin that solved a real problem</h3>
  <p>
    The PagerDuty plugin. During an incident, clicking to the on-call engineer for a service became
    one click from the catalog. No Slack hunting, no wiki pages, no "who owns payments again?"
    Incident response time dropped measurably.
  </p>

  <h3>We removed four plugins nobody used</h3>
  <p>
    The Kubernetes pod status plugin, a cost explorer, a GitHub Insights panel, and a CI status
    widget that duplicated what was already in GitHub. Fewer things to maintain, fewer things to break,
    less cognitive load for new users trying to understand what Backstage is for.
  </p>

  <h2>What Moved the Needle</h2>
  <p>
    Weekly active users went from 8 to 40+ over about 10 weeks. The changes that drove it:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Catalog quality enforcement</strong> — the platform is only useful if the data is trustworthy. Once engineers trusted the catalog, they started using it.</li>
    <li><strong>Templates that work out of the box</strong> — two engineers used the new service template in the first week and told their teams. Word of mouth is faster than documentation.</li>
    <li><strong>Solving an incident pain point</strong> — the PagerDuty link gave Backstage a reason to be open during incidents, not just onboarding.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Lesson</h2>
  <p>
    Internal platforms compete with muscle memory. Engineers already know how to find things — it
    just takes longer and hurts more. To displace those habits, the platform has to be noticeably
    faster or more reliable on something engineers do frequently.
  </p>
  <p>
    That means ignoring feature requests that sound good but happen rarely, and obsessing over the
    three or four workflows that happen every day. Get those right and the adoption follows. Try to
    be everything and you end up used by nobody.
  </p>
</WritingLayout>
